text.text: A Guide to Soho

Madame JoJo might have met her end and famously shady backstreets may have been cleaned up, but the bright lights of Soho still tickle us pink. This is, after all, one of the world’s most colourful neighbourhoods and London’s premiere gaybourhood. Trot on down for historic pubs and kinky shops, gay bars and oyster bars, world class restaurants and the best tasting trotters we ever did try. Oh how we love you Soho, let’s have it large.
Best for... bargain fresh pasta on the go

tip.text:
There might be better places to eat so well for so little £ in these populous ends, but we don’t know many. Al Dente is a pastificio: a takeaway pasta shop where you might grab an indulgent takeaway lunch during the week; buy some tortellini for a slap up meal at home; or come in the evening for a quick, casual feeding. In all cases, you're gonna be extremely satisfied with what your mouth finds.

The pasta, all handmade and served at just the right cottura al dente, is flippin' exquisite, delectable stuff. We sampled some melt-in-the-mouth green tortelli (spinach, mushrooms, ricotta cheese and truffle); and a decadent yet refined carbonara. Yes this is pure, authentic Italian cooking and, with dishes around the £6.50-7 mark, it's an excellent cheap eat. Get in, grab a plate of pasta and a glass of wine, chomp it, sip it, feel good, reflect on your standing in the world, then move slowly onwards.

tip.text:
Set up by two best friends and run with the same passion that inspired them to open the place, 10 Greek Street is a right ripper of a restaurant. Inside the interiors are simple with white tiled walls, rustic-industrial furnishings and their Mediterranean menu written up on big chalk boards. Sit up at the open kitchen with a glass of wine and a couple of small plates or come for dinner and indulge in a few more. While the menu changes frequently, you can expect things along the lines of prawns with piquillo peppers and chorizo or venison with celeriac, kale and chestnuts.

Hot tip: if you like your wine, request the little black book - this is essentially a handwritten book with a list of special wines sourced from private collectors, suppliers and their own personal cellar.

tip.text: One of three Tap coffee shops, this is the one where the magic actually happens. These guys roast their own blend in store once a week with beans from Colombia, Guatemala, Costa Rica and El Salvador. If you're lucky enough to find a seat, then sit and enjoy your coffee in the most stylish of surroundings. Go for an espresso (served with a small shot of oolong green tea), a filtered blend (these guys take a lot of pride in their filter coffee) or a perfectly foamed latte.

text.text: It sounds unlikely but this cafe boasts a sprawling space in central Soho. Swing by for coffee made with love, tempting cakes, sandwiches and smiley staff who have big respect for their beans. If you're an out-of-office type, there's also ample space to hunker down with your laptop.
Best for... pig trotters and bao

tip.text:
Bao in Soho (and now Fitzrovia) is one of those rare places where the hype is totally deserved. Accept the fact that you'll be waiting in a queue to get in - it's part of the experience and trust us when we say their pig totter croquettes are worth braving wind, rain and thunderstorms for.

Of course what people come here for is the bao - those soft white pillows stuffed with the likes of braised pork, peanut powder, fermented greens and coriander. But while the bao are delicious don't let that distract you from the trotter nuggets, pig blood cake and guinea fowl chi shiang rice. For something wet, choose from a tiny list of cocktails or just go for the comforting peanut milk.

tip.text:
This spot is modelled on an American style dive bar, so don't expect anything glitz or glam, partner. But what you can expect is live music every of the goddamn week. The vibe of this place is classic blues bar - you know, like the ones they have State-side.

The food might not be all that and from what we've heard the 'facilities' leave something to be desired. But hey, we can't all be perfect. Don't let that stop you from sliding through and catching a bunch of talented musicians doing their thang.

text.text: This spot just off Carnaby Street is modelled on an American style dive bar, putting on (exclusively) live blues every night of the goddamn week. Don't expect anything too glitz or glam here - the drink selection is pretty much just beer and the facilities leave something to be desired but it does attract some hugely talented musicians and quite frankly we like a bit of dive to offset the swankier bars in the area.
Best for... a dive into a treasure trove of music

tip.text:
This is a Soho institution: a record emporium that's a true treasure trove for diggers who like their sounds eclectic: with reggae, disco, hip-hop, jazz, soul, post-punk and everything that falls between the gaps represented. Set up in the 90s and tied to the label Soul Jazz records, Sounds of the Universe is a friendly, welcoming place to come for a browse - either from the recent releases on the first floor, or from the second hand cuts in the basement.

All kinds of DJs, artists and connoisseurs have rolled in here including Prince, Moodymann, and Questlove - it's a Soho stalwart and with good reason.

tip.text:
Good friend dolls out fried chicken reminiscent of night markets in Taiwan - you know the ones you haven't been to but you'd like to one day, when you're cool, rich and not famous. They've even shipped the oven all the way from the motherland to make sure the chicken's just as crunchy and tender as the real deal.

You can go for crisptastic little nuggets or get the big ol' chicken breast, sliced up and, er, 'flat packed', if you will, to be as large as... your head. Once it's been tossed in three different flours and double fried then it's up to you to cover it in your choice of magical powders (also known as seasonings). Some of them are a little rogue so - as with most unknown powders - go easy on them. We did like the plum though.

tip.text:
The Yard is - unsurprisingly perhaps - famed for its yard, with its lovely wrap-around balcony, its flattering fairy lights and its soothing, shimmering outdoor heaters. It's tucked away down a chandelier-lit alleyway off Rupert Street, away from the madness of pump-it-up Soho, and packed with classy gay men and friendly Marlboro-light smokers. When it's your turn to head to the bar, take a gander at the luscious cocktail menu, the stunning blue neon lights, the exposed-brick walls - and the, um, nice-looking topless bartenders.

The Yard has only very recently been saved after a long standing battle with Soho's property developers, so show your support: go have a drink with your friends or chirp on the ol' twitter.

Best for... a taste of the old Soho

tip.text:
Combine history and hedonism with a trip to Soho's most celebrated watering hole. Cult figures like Bob Dylan and Francis Bacon have wet their tongues at The French House in the past, so why not add your name to the illustrious list?

This Grade II listed building is strict about retaining a certain distinguished air - that means no TV, music, machines or mobile phones. It might be a bit of a squeeze inside at times but spilling out onto the street is part of the place's tradition, as any regular will gladly tell you. Lager comes in half-pints only and real ale is nowhere to be seen but the wine and champagne selection is extensive.

Upstairs a kitchen headed up by Neil Borthwick pumps out Frenchy foods like pig's head terrine, spatchcock quail and Jerusalem artichoke soup.

tip.text:
This might just be London's most relaxed member's club. Make your way through a nondescript entrance on Greek Street down the shabby, carpeted stairs; sign in at the door (or don’t); and settle into what feels like the set of a mafia drama. On the walls and ceilings are framed photos of boxers, footballers and gangster-looking types. There's only a couple of dimly lit tables and a tiny smoking area out back through the toilets, and while the drinks menu isn't extensive, almost everything seems to be four quid.

This feels like one of the last bastions of 'Old Soho', a place of hedonistic community spirit, a proper family affair where everyone that comes through the door seems to be close friends with the owner, Trisha. Get chatting with Danny (Trisha's son) and he'll give you the low down on the club's history as an illegal gambling den and, if he trusts you, his technique for dealing with troublemakers.

Live music on intermittent weekends makes this a good spot for a lively drink on Fridays and Saturdays, or just swing by in the week for a cheap drink in Soho. Technically a member's club, you either have to wheedle your way in or cough up a fiver for the year.

text.text:
This might just be London's most lax member's club. Make your way through a shabby, nondescript entrance on Greek Street, sign in at the door (or not) and settle into what seems like the set of a mafia drama. On the walls are framed photos of boxers, footballers and gangsters, the drinks menu isn't impressive and you can expect dirty looks from the regulars on arrival. But don't let any of that put you off - on the weekend this place is party central and if you're after a 'genuine' speakeasy bar, this is it. 

Wheedle your way past the bouncer or cough up £5 membership for the year.
Best for... wannabe Brooklynites

tip.text:
Bringing a bit of gritty, grungy Brookyln to Soho is Spuntino: a dimly lit bar with no sign outside which has benches instead of tables, high stools at the bar and cracked tiles forming the décor. The bar does some small plates of Italian-American food (the buttermilk fried chicken sharing plate involves a pancake, chilli and much maple syrup), fine-ass drinks, and now indulgent bottomless brunches from 10am-2pm. Park up for the likes of steak and eggs, aubergine and tomato ragu with crumbly morsels of feta on toast, and dippy eggs and soldiers while you guzzle mimosas and Bloody Marys.

Walk-ins only (but can take bookings for groups over 6), and with fried chicken that good you can imagine the queues for a seat once the evening is in full swing.

Keep an eye on that tab too - it could make some serious dents in the old wallet.
Best for... transporting yourself back to the 30s

tip.text: Step out of reality and into a glamorous, Art Deco world perfect for playing out illicit affairs and high-end dodgy dealings. This basement bar underneath Brasserie Zedel is a beautiful, French bar fitted out with dark wood, leather seating and a ridiculous but fabulous tiger print carpet. Cocktails are pricey at £14 but worth it for the added drama of the place. Go for a classic (Martini, Whiskey Sour, Daiquiri) or something a little more reflective of the bar like The French Aperitif made with gin, byrrh, lemon juice, orgeat, bitter lemon and cherry bitters.

tip.text:
The space at Polpetto is warm, tightly packed with customers and decorated with farmhouse finesse. Take a pew, prosecco in hand at the aperitivo bar or squeeze yourself among the rest of the restaurant’s fans. Polpetto is a little more intimate, a little more experimental and a little more cute than its sister Polpo restaurants - this is where all sorts of new dishes come out the open kitchen to be tested on the likes of you.

On the plate are small Italian offerings like spicy pork and fennel meatballs, swordfish tartare and Piedmontese peppers with white anchovies - it’s a grown-up concept made informal by a toe-tapping playlist and flirty offerings like the strawberry and prosecco slushie for afters. Oh and for god’s sake try the orange and Campari cake.

Best for... an opulent trip to a Hong-Kong speakeasy

tip.text:
If you thought Bun House had winning interiors, then just wait till you set foot in Tea Room just below. The retro Cantonese design continues but the tiling, neon signage and attention to detail is ramped up a notch. We perused the drinks menu printed on a vintage-looking newspaper and pretended we were hedonistic businessmen in 60s Hong Kong. The cocktails may be pricey but with damn good reason; ours was made with toasted maple infused baijiu, smoked tea liqueur, a lapsang tea smoked century pear and five spices. Some real grown up flavours.

With lots of small bites you can try all sorts without completely breaking the bank - be it perfectly spiced lamb shoulder skewers, the most refreshing prickly cucumbers or rich duck tongue fries. We thoroughly enjoyed the way their clay pot dishes crisped up beautifully at the bottom for a many textured rice topped with a subtly flavoured tea egg. For full immersion, you'll want to finish with the red chocolate bun, which balances the sweetness of chocolate with a touch of pig's blood. Yep, Tea Room has just the right amount of pomp and tea ceremony in our opinion.

text.text:
This is a welcome dose of opulent escapism: a speakeasy with a retro Cantonese design that lures you into thinking you're a hedonistic businessman in 60s Hong Kong with the budget to match. The cocktails may be pricey but with damn good reason; ours was made with toasted maple infused baijiu, smoked tea liqueur, a lapsang tea smoked century pear and five spices. Some real grown up flavours.

With lots of small bites you can try all sorts without completely breaking the bank - be it perfectly spiced lamb shoulder skewers, the most refreshing prickly cucumbers or rich duck tongue fries. Yep, Tea Room has just the right amount of pomp and tea ceremony in our opinion - but please watch that bill!
